Since each outcome has equal probability, we can use the following formula:

$\qquad  \text{Probability} = \dfrac{\text{Relevant outcomes}}{{\text{Size of the sample space}}}$ 

Since there are $3$ dangerous areas where Carl can either fall or stay on his feet, the size of the sample space is $2^3 = \red{8}$.

To find relevant outcomes for small sample spaces, we can write out the sample space and count. 

Letting "S"  represent Carl staying on his feet and "F" represent Carl falling, the sample space for Carl running through $3$ dangerous areas is:

Falls | Relevant outcomes 
:-: | :-: | :-: | :-:
$0$ |{SSS} 
$1$ |{FSS, SFS, SSF}
$2$ |{FFS, FSF, SFF}
$3$ |{FFF}
Total| $\red{8}$
$\qquad$

